The exception is the last two elements. We can always take the smallest available number for each $$$q_i$$$ satisfying $$$i \lt n-1$$$. To do this we maintain an array of bools of already taken numbers, and then iterate over it to find the smallest available number satisfying $$$p_i
eq q_i$$$ which is also not checked in the array, and then check it (we took it).
Now consider $$$(p_{n-1},p_{n})$$$ and we want $$$(q_{n-1},q_{n})$$$ to be lexicographically minimal while satisfying $$$p_{n-1}
eq q_{n-1}$$$ and $$$p_{n}
eq q_{n}$$$. Let $$$a$$$ and $$$b$$$ be the last two unused numbers in the array of bools with $$$a \lt b$$$. We try to take $$$(q_{n-1},q_{n}) = (a,b)$$$. If $$$a=p_{n-1}$$$ or $$$b=p_{n}$$$, then we take $$$(q_{n-1},q_{n}) = (b,a)$$$. If $$$(a,b)$$$ isn't valid, then $$$(b,a)$$$ is. The proof is left as an exercise to the reader.
This solution runs in $$$O(n^2)$$$ and can be optimized to $$$O(n \ log \ n)$$$.
